<DOC><DOCNO> AP890615-0146 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2136EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-15 0239</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Thousands Of Radical Students Clash With Riot Police</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of radical students foughtriot police with rocks and firebombs Thursday to protest agovernment crackdown on campus activism and dissident movements.   Students clashed with police in front of at least fouruniversities. No injuries or arrests were reported.   Fierce fighting broke out at Yonsei and Sogang universities inwestern Seoul, where about 2,000 students, many hurling rocks andfirebombs, tried to march into the streets.   Police, armed with padded fatigues, helmets and shields, blockedthe students by hurling back rocks. They did not use tear gas.   Smaller clashes also were reported at two other universities inthe capital.   The students criticized a continuing crackdown by President RohTae-woo's government on dissident movements and demanded thatstudent leaders be allowed to take part in a world youth festival inthe North Korean capital of Pyongyang on July 1-8.   Sogang students were furious about a police raid on their schoollast week to seize propaganda materials for the Pyongyang festival.Sogang, a Jesuit school, is the headquarters of radical studentscampaigning to go to the sports and cultural event.   Seoul officials accused communist North Korea of using thefestival to promote dissident activity in South Korea.   The Koreas have been bitter rivals since their land was dividedin 1945 at the end of World War II. They fought the Korean War in1950-53.</TEXT></DOC>